  "prompt": "Are ductile metals also malleable?",
  "response": "Yes, ductile metals are generally also malleable. Ductility refers to a material's ability to deform under tensile stress, which means it can be drawn into wires without breaking. Malleability, on the other hand, refers to a material's ability to deform under compressive stress, allowing it to be hammered or rolled into thin sheets.\n\nMost ductile materials, like gold, silver, copper, and aluminum, exhibit a high degree of malleability as well. Therefore, many metals that are ductile are also capable of being shaped into various forms without fracturing, making them both ductile and malleable.",
